07573nam a22008775i 9781478023197DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222023ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780231977 a10.1515/97814780231972doi  a(DE-B1597)644536  a(OCoLC)1347271390  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aD843 7aPHO0050002bisacsh  aAP 94900qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/8157:00aCold War Camera /ced. by Erina Duganne, Thy Phu, Andrea Noble. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (424 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tCold War: Camera An Introduction -- tVisual Alliances -- t1 Ernest Cole’s House of Bondage, the United States Information Agency, and the Cultural Politics of Race in the Cold War -- t2 Icon of Solidarity: The Revolutionary Vietnamese Woman in Vietnam, Palestine, and Iran -- t3 Group Material’s “Art for the Future”: Visualizing Transnational Solidarity at the End of the Global Cold War -- t4 Interrogating the Cold War’s Geo-Politics from Down South: Chile from Within (1990) and the Construction of a Situated Visuality -- t5 Decolonization and Nonalignment: African Futures, Lost and Found -- tPhoto Essays -- t6 Bifurcated and Parallel Histories -- t7 Preservation of Terror -- tStructures of Seeing -- t8 Ending World War II: The Visual Literacy Class in Cold War Human Rights -- t9 “Planted There Like Human Flags”: Photographs of the High Arctic and Cold War Anxiety, 1951 – 1956 -- t10 Urban Albums, Village Forms: Chinese Family Photographs and the Cold War -- t11 Travel, Space, and Belonging in Soviet Domestic Photo Collections of the Cold War Era -- t12 Exhibiting Ethnic Minorities, Democratizing History: Cold War Legacies and the Jews in Poland’s Visible Sphere -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCold War Camera explores the visual mediation of the Cold War and illuminates photography’s role in shaping the ways it was prosecuted and experienced. The contributors show how the camera stretched the parameters of the Cold War beyond dominant East-West and US-USSR binaries and highlight the significance of photography from across the global South. Among other topics, the contributors examine the production and circulation of the iconic figure of the “revolutionary Vietnamese woman” in the 1960s and 1970s; photographs connected with the coming of independence and decolonization in West Africa; family photograph archives in China and travel snapshots by Soviet citizens; photographs of apartheid in South Africa; and the circulation of photographs of Inuit Canadians who were relocated to the extreme Arctic in the 1950s. Highlighting the camera’s capacity to envision possible decolonialized futures, establish visual affinities and solidarities, and advance calls for justice to redress violent proxy conflicts, this volume demonstrates that photography was not only crucial to conducting the Cold War, it is central to understanding it.Contributors. Ariella Azoulay, Jennifer Bajorek, Erina Duganne, Evyn Lê Espiritu Gandhi, Eric Gottesman, Tong Lam, Karintha Lowe, Ángeles Donoso Macaya, Darren Newbury, Andrea Noble, Sarah Parsons, Gil Pasternak, Thy Phu, Oksana Sarkisova, Olga Shevchenko, Laura Wexler, Guigui Yao, Donya Ziaee, Marta Ziętkiewicz  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPhotography / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAzoulay, Ariella Aïsha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBajorek, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuganne, Erina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuga